## Architecture

This project uses Clean Architecture. Data flows strictly inward:

```
cmd/app/
  main.go               → binary entrypoint; calls app.Run()

internal/app/
  app.go                → dependency wiring and server startup

internal/entity/
  *.go                  → domain structs; no framework or DB imports

internal/usecase/
  *.go                  → business logic; depends only on entity types and repo interfaces

internal/controller/http/
  router.go             → route registration
  handler/              → HTTP handlers; call usecases, write JSON responses
  middleware/           → logger and CORS middleware

internal/repo/
  persistent/           → DB layer; implements repo interfaces defined in usecase files
  webapi/               → external HTTP calls

pkg/
  logger/               → Logger interface + {{.Logger}} implementation
  client/               → shared HTTP client
  constants/            → application-wide constants
  utils/                → shared utilities

config/
  config.go             → Viper config loader
```

**Rule:** handlers call usecases; usecases call repos. Nothing crosses layers in the other direction.

---

## Key Conventions

- **Logger:** Always import `{{.Module}}/pkg/logger`. Never import a concrete logger (`go.uber.org/zap`, `github.com/rs/zerolog`, etc.) outside of `pkg/logger/`.
{{- if or (eq .DB "postgres-gorm") (eq .DB "sqlite-gorm") (eq .DB "mysql-gorm")}}
- **Entities:** Domain structs live in `internal/entity/`. GORM struct tags (`gorm:"..."`) are applied directly on entity fields.
{{- else}}
- **Entities:** Domain structs live in `internal/entity/`. They carry no DB-layer imports or tags.
{{- end}}
- **Config:** Application config is loaded from `application.yml` and `.env` via Viper and godotenv. Add new keys to both files.
- **Repo interfaces:** Each usecase file defines the repo interface it needs. The concrete implementation lives in `internal/repo/persistent/`. Never import a concrete repo type from a usecase.

